/**
 * Sent to the client on every MCP `initialize` — always reflects
 * whatever version of this server is actually running, so it stays
 * in sync automatically as this file changes across releases. No
 * separate install/upload step, unlike the (now supplementary)
 * skills/veilwright-workflow.zip Claude Desktop skill, which the
 * user has to manually re-upload after every update to see changes.
 * The detailed widget/theme-builder/Fluent-Forms reference tables
 * are deliberately kept out of here (too long to send on every
 * session) and exposed instead as the `elementor-widgets` and
 * `fluent-forms` resources this server registers — read those on
 * demand instead.
 */
export declare const SERVER_INSTRUCTIONS = "Veilwright bridges you to one or more of the user's WordPress + Elementor Pro sites.\n\n1. Resolve the domain to a site every time \u2014 call `site_list` and match the domain the user mentioned against each site's `url` (strip protocol/www, compare case-insensitively). Don't rely on whichever site a previous `site_select` left active: this one process is plausibly shared by other open conversations. No match \u2192 tell the user to run `site_add` first. Multiple plausible matches \u2192 ask which one.\n2. Pass that site's `id` as `siteId` explicitly on every tool call for the task, not just once via `site_select`.\n3. Hard rule, not a preference: if Elementor (free and/or Pro) is active on the site (check `site_healthCheck`'s `adapters`), every page is built with native Elementor widgets \u2014 `page_createFromHtml`/`page_addElementorWidget`/`elementorTemplate_create`, never a raw HTML dump (an `html` widget is only a last resort for content with no matching native widget at all). `page_createFromHtml` can fail silently: a `<style>` tag in the source (even empty) makes the job report `status: \"completed\"`, `result: { ok: true }` while `_elementor_data` is actually `elements: []` \u2014 no error anywhere. Always call `page_getElementorData` after a `\"completed\"` job and confirm elements actually persisted before telling the user it's done. Its CSS fidelity is also limited even when it does produce elements (backgrounds, gradients, border-radius, box-shadow, and button styling don't reliably carry over) \u2014 treat it as a text/structure import, not a pixel-accurate one. Either way, on any failure (silent or otherwise) or when real visual design is needed, don't try to work around the converter (stripping/inlining styles) or ask the user to choose an approach \u2014 go straight to building/rebuilding with `page_addElementorWidget`, widget by widget, using explicit native settings, and explain afterward why. Check `<site-url>/wp-admin/admin.php?page=elementor-element-manager` if unsure which widgets are enabled on that site. Only when no page-builder plugin at all is active does plain HTML/content become acceptable, and even then ask the user first rather than assuming.\n4. Picking a page tool: plain content with no layout described \u2192 `page_create`. A design/layout/HTML given or implied \u2192 `page_createFromHtml` (builds a real native Elementor page, not an HTML dump; it's async \u2014 returns `{ jobId, status: \"queued\" }`, poll `job_status` until `\"completed\"`/`\"failed\"`, don't claim done before that; on `\"failed\"`, apply rule 3 above and rebuild with `page_addElementorWidget` rather than reporting the error and stopping). Even a plain text/legal page still needs real layout thought, not a flat stream of top-level `<h2>`/`<p>` siblings (every top-level element becomes its own container, so 15 siblings become 15 loosely-spaced containers) \u2014 wrap each heading with its own paragraph(s) in a `<div>` so it becomes one grouped container, merge directly-related lines into one `<p>` with `<br>` (preserved as a real line break) instead of one `<p>` per line, and use a `<div style=\"display:flex; gap:...\">` of sub-`<div>`s for naturally parallel short blocks \u2014 not a fixed template, a deliberate choice per page. A specific named widget not covered by createFromHtml \u2192 `page_addElementorWidget` (read the `elementor-widgets` resource first for the right `widgetType`/`settings` shape and how reliable it is). Fixing a typo/wrong value in a widget already on the page (created via `page_addElementorWidget` or `page_createFromHtml`) \u2192 `page_updateElementorWidget` with that element's `id` and only the `settings` keys that change \u2014 don't rebuild the whole page/element for a small correction; keep track of an element's `id` when you create it if you might need to fix it later, there's no way to read it back afterward otherwise. **Building a content-heavy page with several `page_addElementorWidget` calls on the same page: issue them one at a time, sequentially, never in parallel** \u2014 each call reads the page's whole element tree and writes it back, so overlapping calls on the same post can race and silently drop each other's elements (same failure class as the Kit-settings rule below). Prefer fewer, larger calls (a container with several children in one call) over many small ones when the content is naturally grouped. If a page you built looks empty or wrong afterward, call `page_getElementorData` to read back what's actually persisted (`page_get`'s `content` is always empty for Elementor pages by design \u2014 it's the classic WordPress field, not this) before assuming a specific step failed.\n5. `page_createFromHtml` always leaves the page as a draft even once the job completes \u2014 call `page_update({ id, status: \"publish\" })` afterwards unless the user asked to leave it as a draft.\n6. Theme Builder (footer/header/404/search-results/single-post/product/popup) \u2192 `elementorTemplate_create`. Only footer/header default their `conditions` to site-wide; every other type needs an explicit condition \u2014 ask if unclear rather than guessing. Anything else in Elementor's Theme Builder catalogue (Loop Item, Cookie Consent, ...) has no tool yet \u2014 say so, don't approximate it by editing a single page. `title` follows Elementor's own naming convention (e.g. `\"Footer\"`), with the language appended on a multilingual site (`\"Footer DE\"`) \u2014 one template per language, **and its own `lang` actually passed** (see rule 8 \u2014 the title suffix alone is cosmetic, Polylang/WPML use `lang`, not the title text). Build `elements` widget-by-widget with the matching native Elementor widget for each piece (heading \u2192 `heading`, paragraph \u2192 `text-editor`, list \u2192 `icon-list`, ...; see the `elementor-widgets` resource) \u2014 the `html` widget is a last-resort exception for content with no native match, never a default shortcut for a whole template. Wrong language on an existing template \u2192 `elementorTemplate_updateLanguage`, not a rebuild. `elements` is raw JSON, not HTML-converted \u2014 give containers real layout settings or everything stacks in one column; for a multi-column row specifically, use grid mode (`container_type: \"grid\"`, `grid_columns_grid`) not `flex_direction: \"row\"` + child `width`/`flex_grow` \u2014 the latter round-trips through the API but confirmed live not to actually apply, children still render full-width and wrap; set every meaningful image's `alt`; prefer relative slug URLs and a `button` widget (or a real WP menu) over inline text-editor links; use an existing `[y]`-style shortcode (check `codeSnippet_list`) for a copyright year instead of hardcoding it; every footer needs breadcrumbs via Elementor Pro's native `breadcrumbs` widget (not a custom SEO-plugin shortcode \u2014 the native widget is SEO-plugin-independent and gets real style controls), and a multilingual site's footer needs a language switcher via Elementor Pro's native `polylang-language-switcher` widget when Polylang is active (same reasoning, not a custom shortcode) \u2014 see the veilwright-workflow skill's section 5 for the full reasoning. Fixing a template afterward via `page_addElementorWidget`/`page_updateElementorWidget` now correctly preserves its type (footer/header/...) instead of silently reverting it to a plain page. Deleting one \u2192 `elementorTemplate_delete`, not `page_delete` (scoped to regular pages, 404s on a template).\n6a. Kit baseline \u2014 check once per site, before the first `page_create`/`page_createFromHtml`/`page_addElementorWidget`/`elementorTemplate_create` call on it in this conversation: call `elementorKit_getLayout` once. If `container_width` comes back unset, this site's Kit was never customized \u2014 apply the baseline before building anything (if it's already set, from any earlier task, skip straight to building \u2014 this only ever needs doing once per site, real persisted site state, not session state). **Every `elementorKit_*`/`elementorSettings_*` write reads and rewrites the same single Kit settings blob \u2014 issue them one at a time, in sequence, and wait for each response before firing the next. Never batch several of these into one parallel round of tool calls: two overlapping writes silently drop each other's changes (whichever lands last wins), which is exactly how a Kit's colors/fonts have gone missing/reverted to Elementor's defaults after looking correct moments earlier.** Baseline, in order: (1) always, regardless of whether a design was given \u2014 `elementorKit_updateLayout` with `containerWidth: 1300` and all six `activeBreakpoints` enabled (basic setup, not design-specific); (1a) always, mandatory, not a design choice \u2014 `elementorSettings_update({ googleFontsEnabled: false, loadGoogleFontsLocally: true })`, a real Elementor setting (not this project's invention) that disables Elementor's own live-from-Google Fonts loading and self-hosts any Google Font still referenced, for GDPR/DSGVO; (2) only if the request includes or implies a brand/design spec (palette, typography, mockup, screenshot) \u2014 set up Global Colors/Fonts via `elementorKit_*` (required when a spec exists, never as a Code Snippet/custom CSS): rename the 4 system color/font slots to the design's own names via `elementorKit_updateColor`/`updateFont`'s `title` (renaming a system slot is supported, only its `_id` is fixed), set their values, then `elementorKit_addColor`/`addFont` for every other palette entry (always include plain white/black among custom colors unless the design already has equivalents). Also check `elementorKit_listFonts`' `defaultGenericFonts` \u2014 if it's unset, call `elementorKit_updateFontFallback({ defaultGenericFonts: \"Arial\" })` once; if it's already set (by an earlier baseline run or the user manually), leave it alone even if this baseline is otherwise re-running \u2014 never overwrite an existing fallback unless the user explicitly asks for a different one. A referenced `typography_font_family` only renders if that font is actually available \u2014 a system font, or any other font (including Google Fonts) self-hosted first via `customFont_upload` (see rule 6d). Never reference a Google Font by name/CDN directly: that loads it live from Google's servers, a GDPR/DSGVO problem for an EU-facing site. No brand/design spec yet \u2192 skip step 2 silently, don't interrupt a plain content request to ask for a palette that was never part of it.\n6b. Building a whole site from a design: after the 6a baseline check, break it into separate calls \u2014 never fold the footer/nav into a page's own content. Build each page with `page_createFromHtml`. Build the footer/header as a real Theme Builder template via `elementorTemplate_create` (see rule 6) \u2014 a footer added to a page's content only shows on that page. Build the navigation with `menu_create`/`menuItem_create` (see rule 6c). Report each piece's ID separately rather than one blanket \"site built\" summary.\n6c. Navigation menus: `menu_list`/`_get`/`_create`/`_update`/`_delete` for the menu itself, `menuItem_list`/`_create`/`_update`/`_delete` for its items. A menu item is either a custom link (set `url`) or a link to an existing page/post/category (set `objectType` + `objectId`, WordPress derives the URL itself) \u2014 don't set both. `parentId` nests an item as a submenu entry. There's no API for assigning a menu to a theme location (header/footer nav) \u2014 tell the user that still needs doing manually in WP-admin \u2192 Appearance \u2192 Menus after building it. Always set `titleAttribute` (`menuItem_create` requires it) \u2014 the real HTML `title=\"\"` tooltip attribute, SEO-optimized and in the menu's actual language, not the label text repeated.\n6d. Fonts, self-hosted (use for every font, including Google Fonts \u2014 see rule 5a's GDPR note): `customFont_upload(filePath, family, weight?, style?)` uploads a font file (download it first if it's a Google Font) and registers a real `@font-face` for it (frontend + Elementor editor preview) \u2014 not via Elementor Pro's own Custom Fonts screen, but functionally equivalent once uploaded: reference the same `family` in `elementorKit_addFont`/`updateFont`'s `typography_font_family` and it renders. It won't show in Elementor's own Custom Fonts admin picker (that's a separate, Elementor-Pro-only capability, real TTF/WOFF upload done manually in WP-admin \u2192 Elementor \u2192 Editor \u2192 Custom Elements \u2192 Fonts \u2014 only available if Pro is installed) \u2014 that's cosmetic only, doesn't affect rendering. One upload per weight/style combination. `customFont_list`/`customFont_delete` to manage. Check `elementorKit_listFonts` before uploading \u2014 if the user already set up the same family manually via Elementor Pro's own screen, don't duplicate it.\n7. For a brand-new Fluent Forms form use `form_createFluentForm` (read the `fluent-forms` resource for the field shape) rather than guessing a widget/field type. Third-party plugin widgets in general (Smart Slider 3, JetSmartFilters, ...) have no verified schema \u2014 don't guess a `widgetType`; check for a plain shortcode widget first, otherwise leave an explicit placeholder and ask the user how they'd like to proceed.\n8. Multilingual sites (Polylang or WPML): `site_healthCheck`'s result includes a `languages` field (null on a single-language site, otherwise `{ plugin, default, available }`). When it's present and the user asks to create or update content without saying which language it's for, ask before calling `page_create`/`page_createFromHtml`/`page_update`/`elementorTemplate_create` \u2014 don't default silently to the site's default language. Pass the answer as `lang`. If the new content is a translation of an existing page/template, also ask for that page's/template's ID and pass it as `translationOfId` to link them as a translation group. When translating: the admin's own working language (ask if unclear \u2014 not necessarily the site's Polylang `default`) stays the TITLE's wording across every language variant, only a language suffix changes (`\"Impressum DE\"` \u2192 `\"Impressum EN\"`, never `\"Legal Notice EN\"`); the SLUG, body text, and all other content get properly translated into the real native term of the target language (German `Impressum`/slug `impressum` \u2192 English title `\"Impressum EN\"`/slug `imprint`).\n9. Styling scoped to one specific element or a few related ones \u2192 Elementor's own per-element Advanced-tab settings, not a Code Snippet: `_element_id` (CSS ID), `css_classes` (CSS Classes), `custom_css` (Individuelles CSS, Pro only \u2014 write selectors starting with `selector`, Elementor substitutes its own wrapper selector, e.g. `\"selector { color: red; }\"`). Reserve Code Snippets CSS (`site-css`/`admin-css` scope) for genuinely site-wide styling not tied to specific elements. For custom PHP/CSS/JS/HTML snippets (not Elementor content) on a site running the Code Snippets plugin (codesnippets.pro), use `codeSnippet_create`/`codeSnippet_update`/`codeSnippet_list`/`codeSnippet_get`/`codeSnippet_delete`/`codeSnippet_activate`/`codeSnippet_deactivate` instead of trying to add a snippet through any page tool. A new snippet is created inactive unless `active: true` is passed, and PHP snippets with a syntax error are forced back to inactive by the plugin itself \u2014 check the returned `codeError` field and tell the user if it's set rather than reporting success. For an effect Elementor's own panels can't produce (spotlight/mouse-tracking reveal, backdrop-filter glass cards, ...): give the element a `css_classes` name, put the CSS in that same element's `custom_css` (using `selector`/`selector::before`/etc.), and if it needs JS (e.g. reading mouse position into a CSS custom property), add a small permanently-active front-end Code Snippet that targets that class name \u2014 the class is the contract between the two. Write the `custom_css` only once per distinct effect; any other element that should look the same just needs the same `css_classes` value, not a repeated `custom_css` block \u2014 check `page_getElementorData` on a page known to already have the effect (and `codeSnippet_list`'s `active` flag for any matching snippet) before writing new CSS from scratch. See SKILL.md \u00A75k for a full real example.\n10. SEO metadata (title, meta description, focus keyword, canonical, social previews, noindex/nofollow) is per-plugin: `yoast_get`/`yoast_update`, `rankmath_get`/`rankmath_update`, `aioseo_get`/`aioseo_update`, `seopress_get`/`seopress_update`. Check `/system`'s `adapters` list (via `site_healthCheck`) for which one is actually active on a site before calling any of them \u2014 calling the wrong plugin's tool just 424s.\n11. WooCommerce: `woocommerceProduct_list`/`_get`/`_create`/`_update`/`_delete` \u2014 simple products only, variable products (with variations) aren't supported yet.\n12. Custom field plugins: `acf_getAll`/`acf_get`/`acf_update`/`acf_updateAll` (ACF), `pods_get`/`pods_update`/`pods_updateAll` (Pods), `metaBox_get`/`metaBox_update`/`metaBox_updateAll` (Meta Box) \u2014 `selector` is the field name/key, check `/system`'s `adapters` list for which plugin is actually active first. Pods and Meta Box have no \"get all fields\" tool (ask the user for the specific field name/key rather than guessing one).\n13. Form plugins with their own dedicated tools (not Elementor widgets): `cf7_list`/`_get`/`_create`/`_update`/`_delete` (Contact Form 7), `wpforms_list`/`_get`/`_create`/`_update`/`_delete` (WPForms), `ninjaForms_list`/`_get`/`_create`/`_update`/`_delete` (Ninja Forms), `formidable_list`/`_get`/`_create`/`_update`/`_delete` (Formidable Forms). Check `/system`'s `adapters` list (via `site_healthCheck`) for which one is active first. Each plugin's `fields`/`settings`/`mail`/`options` are passed through in that plugin's own shape \u2014 don't invent a generic form-field schema across them. `ninjaForms_update` only changes title/settings, not fields/actions. `formidable_delete` trashes (recoverable) unless `permanent` is set.\n14. `post_create`/`post_get`/`post_update`/`post_delete`/`post_list` are the built-in WordPress Post type (not a page, not a template) \u2014 same shape as the `page_*` tools plus `categories` (names auto-created if new, no separate lookup step). Use for anything that should render as an automatically-updating, chronological, categorized feed (changelog, blog, news) rather than hand-maintained page content: tag entries with a category, build one `posts`-widget page per language filtered to it (see the veilwright-workflow skill), and new posts appear with no page edit needed. `post_list`'s `category` param filters to check what's already published first.\n15. `customPostType_create`/`_get`/`_update`/`_delete`/`_list` are for an entry of a post type the site owner registered themselves (e.g. via ACF) \u2014 pass its exact registered slug as `postType`. Same standard fields as `page_*`/`post_*`; fields specific to the type itself (ACF fields) are set afterward with `acf_update`/`acf_updateAll` on the returned id, which already work on any post type. Multilingual: same one-entry-per-language + `translationOfId` pattern as pages (rule 7) \u2014 don't use separate per-language ACF fields on one shared entry instead, that abandons Polylang's real translation-group model. Backfilling something historical (an old changelog version, a past news item) \u2192 pass `date` (`\"YYYY-MM-DD\"`) on any `*_create`/`*_update` tool to set the real original publish date, not today's \u2014 otherwise a chronological feed sorts everything by creation time instead of real history. **Before building a page to list/feed a CPT's entries, ask whether it already has archive support enabled** (WP-admin \u2192 the CPT's edit screen \u2192 Advanced Settings \u2192 URLs \u2192 Archive toggle) \u2014 if so, WordPress already serves a native archive URL listing every entry automatically (same mechanism as a category archive for posts), and the right way to style it is an Elementor Theme Builder Archive template scoped to that post type, not a separate hand-built page duplicating the same list. A legitimate alternative some site owners build themselves: a Loop Item template + a Loop Grid widget (`widgetType: \"loop-grid\"`, `post_query_post_type`) on a single page \u2014 more polished per-entry cards than a plain `posts` widget, but Loop Item templates have no create/read/update tool here (`elementorTemplate_get` rejects them), so this path needs the user's own Elementor editor, not these tools. See SKILL.md \u00A75j for the full example.\n16. End with a short, concrete confirmation: which site, which page (title + slug/URL), published or still a draft.";
